Title:
SilkETW & SilkService

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
SilkETW and SilkService are C#/.NET wrappers around Windows Event Tracing for Windows (ETW) designed to simplify collecting and consuming ETW telemetry for research and introspection. They abstract ETW session/provider complexity and emit normalized JSON that can be written to disk, Windows Event Log, or shipped to external systems (e.g., Elasticsearch/HELK). SilkService runs SilkETW “headless” as a Windows service and supports multiple concurrent collectors via an XML configuration (user and kernel sessions, provider names/guids, keywords, output targets). The project also integrates YARA scanning to tag/filter collected event data, enabling detection of behaviors like in-memory .NET execution (e.g., execute-assembly) based on ETW payloads. It’s useful to both Red Teams (telemetry research, understanding detection surfaces) and Blue Teams (threat hunting, custom telemetry pipelines). It’s interesting because it operationalizes “free” high-fidelity Windows telemetry with flexible output and automation, while remaining relatively lightweight to deploy.

Technical Focus:
- Windows ETW user vs kernel trace sessions (providers, keywords)
- C#/.NET ETW consumption via Microsoft.Diagnostics.Tracing.TraceEvent
- JSON event normalization/serialization for downstream analytics
- Windows service-based continuous collection (SilkService) with XML config
- Output sinks: file, Windows Event Log, HTTP/URL to ELK-style endpoints
- YARA-based tagging/filtering of ETW event content (notably .NET runtime events)

Use Cases:
- Threat hunting pipelines: collect ETW and forward to ELK/HELK for analytics
- Researching Windows telemetry coverage for specific attacker behaviors/tools
- Detecting suspicious .NET activity (JIT/Loader/Interop) and in-memory execution via YARA on ETW
- Collecting kernel process/image-load telemetry to identify tool execution patterns
- Building/validating detections based on specific ETW providers and event fields
- Running multi-provider ETW collection at scale using a configurable Windows service

